I'm confused, does the submarine actually contain the brain of Ivan, or a digital copy of his consciousness? I understand that a central conceit of the article is that the submarine really is Ivan, based on the framing of the transformation of Ivan's mind and body. However, on a philosophical level, this skirts over questions regarding the nature of self and consciousness, which nagged at me while I was reading through. In my eyes, the submarine isn't Ivan, because based on what I read, his brain wasn't literally removed from his head, merely that it was copied, kind of like the brain scans from SOMA, so that -1 isn't Ivan, but merely a facsimile.

Besides this, the writing is very competent. However, I found the interviews, particularly the first, to be lacking. If the story must be presented through dialouge, then I assume a goal of this is to develop pathos. However, I don't have much sympathy for Peter, which is attributable to the blandness of his dialogue, which in turn makes him come off as a little nonchalant at times. For instance, when he says  when describing the condition of his brother. One would assume that with such an intense relationship of sorts, characterised by a range of both positive and negative emotions, he would speak as if he were more invested that he seems to be. Ultimately, the interviews don't really help to convey the notion of a tragic connection between -1 and -2.







